Abstract

   This document enumerates the scheme of choosing subnets by most
   significant bit (msb) of the host portion of the address as described
   in RFC 1219.  Two tables provide the specific information for class B
   (/16) networks and class C (/24) networks.  It is intended to aid
   network planners in adopting an addressing allocation scheme which is
   "renumbering friendly."
                                                                     

Introduction

   The Procedure for Enterprise/Internet Renumbering (PIER) working
   group of the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) has been
   developing a series informational documents to aid in the process of
   renumbering IP networks.  In addition, the group has decided to
   provide informational documents to aid in the design of IP networks
   to make them "renumbering friendly."

   This document provides information to the network planner on how to
   assign subnetworks in a manner which is condusive to easy
   renumbering if a change in subnet mask is required.  It should be
   noted that this procedure is only necessary on equipment and
   protocols that do not support variable length subnet masks (VLSMs),
   which is the large percentage of the equipment currently in use.
   The best solution to this problem is to adopt a interior routing
   protocol that supports VLSMs, such as OSPF or RIPv2.

   A much more technical desciption of this technique is presented in
   RFC 1219 [1].  The material presented below is purely practical,
   that is, it contains that actual computed values for assigning
   subnets from the most significant bit (msb) of the host portion of
   the address, while assigning the hosts addresses from the least
   significant bit (lsb).

   The data is presented for a traditional class B network (A.B/16) and a
   traditional class C network (A.B.C/24).  By ordering subnets in the
   order presented it is possible to relax or constrict the subnet mask
   to fit the changing needs of your network topology.  The transitions
   between number of subnet bits are noted.  That is, once the first
   subnet for a range is used, the smallest number of subnet bits is
   noted.  For example, if the first four subnets were used, the
   minimally required subnet would only be 2 bits (2^2 = 4), but as
   soon as the fifth subnet is allocated the minimum number of bits is
   three.  Transitions occur at the 2nd, 3rd, 5th, 9th, 17th, 33rd,
   etc. subnet assignment.  

Example

   Assume that the first estimate on the maximum number of hosts per
   network is 6.  A subnet mask of 255.255.255.248 is chosen to get a
   series of 30 networks each with 6 hosts (assuming a class C (/24)
   network).  Subnets are then assigned in a sequential decimal order.

   net1: A.B.C.0-7
   net2: A.B.C.8-15
   net3: A.B.C.16-23
   net4: A.B.C.24-31
   net5: A.B.C.32-39
   net6: A.B.B.40-47
   

   Then there is a shift in network topology, or in staff assignments
   or some other reason and theose changes require an increase to 14
   hosts per subnet.  In order to achieve a series of 14 network each
   with 14 hosts a subnet mask of 255.255.255.240 is required.  The
   networks are now:
   
   net1': A.B.C.0-15
   net2': A.B.C.16-31
   net3': A.B.C.32-47
   net4': A.B.C.48-63
   net5': A.B.C.64-79
   net6': A.B.C.80-95
   
   It is clear that the hosts on net2, net4 and net6 will need to be
   renumbered onto nets net4', net5' and net6'.
   
   If on the otherhand network numbers are assigned as suggested:
   
   net1: A.B.C.0-7
   net2: A.B.C.128-135
   net3: A.B.C.64-71
   net4: A.B.C.192-199
   net5: A.B.C.32-39
   net6: A.B.C.160-167
   
   Then changing the mask would generate the following new networks:
   
   net1': A.B.C.0-15
   net2': A.B.C.128-143
   net3': A.B.C.64-79
   net4': A.B.C.192-207
   net5': A.B.C.32-47
   net6': A.B.C.160-175
   
   All of the hosts currently in the net1 can remain in the new net1', etc.
   This can save a large amount of time and administrative hassle especially
   in the DNS and any network management stations.
